Bundled dependencies — permissive (MIT / ISC / Apache-2.0 / BSD)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
trafilaturacore's HTML-cleaning pillar (TypeScript) and its extraction core (the Rust
crate + its napi binding) are built on the following open-source libraries, used
under their respective permissive licenses.

TypeScript runtime (always installed):
  @trafilaturacore/native    — the in-repo napi-rs binding around the Rust extraction
                          core (private workspace package; ships the prebuilt
                          native addon). Apache-2.0 (this repo).
  sanitize-html         — the default HTML cleaner (the cleaning levels). MIT.
  parse5                — WHATWG-compliant HTML normalization. MIT.
  linkedom              — the DOM for metadata + cleaning. ISC.
  prettier              — HTML pretty-printing. MIT.
  html-minifier-terser  — HTML minification (bundles terser, BSD-2-Clause). MIT.
  chardet, iconv-lite   — byte→string decoding. MIT.
  commander             — CLI argument parsing. MIT.

Optional TypeScript (installed only if the consumer opts into the hardened backend):
  dompurify             — opt-in "hardened" cleaner backend.
                          MPL-2.0 OR Apache-2.0 (used under Apache-2.0).
  jsdom                 — DOM for the hardened backend. MIT.

Rust crate dependencies (compiled into the native addon; classifier inference is a
pure-Rust GBDT evaluator over the XGBoost JSON dump — no ONNX/onnxruntime):
  napi, napi-derive     — Node-API bindings. MIT.
  dom_query             — html5ever-based DOM. MIT.
  tendril               — zero-copy strings. MIT OR Apache-2.0.
  regex, serde, serde_json, thiserror, url — MIT OR Apache-2.0.
  html-escape           — output escaping. MIT.

These are dependencies, not vendored source; their full license texts ship in their
respective npm/crates packages, so a plain install already carries each notice. If
you instead redistribute a bundled or vendored build that inlines these, reproduce
their MIT/ISC/BSD/Apache notices.
